description: Exploit and remediate a SQL Injection exposure. All or part of an SQL command is built using unvalidated user input. This could be used to alter query logic to bypass security checks, read sensitive data, or to insert additional statements that modify the back-end database.
topics: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command
title: SQL Injection
trophyDescription: The candidate can remediate simple SQL Injection exposures in Java.

infoList.title: Starting the exercise
infoList.description: When starting the exercise you will be presented with an Ubuntu desktop. Wait for Eclipse IDE and Firefox to launch.

infoList.title: Eclipse
infoList.description: Switch to Eclipse, click on the "Servers" tab, then click on "Start the Server" to launch the application server.

infoList.title: Firefox
infoList.description: Switch to Firefox, browse to: http://www.vulnerableapp.com:8050 . Login to the Vulnerable Application using the following credentials: user / password

infoList.title: Finishing the exercise
infoList.description: When you have completed the exercise, browse to Running Exercises" and click on "Mark Completed". Provisional results will be available in the "History" tab.

infoList.title: Troubleshooting
infoList.description: Restore source code: if you accidentally break the app's functionality, you can reset the app to the original source code using the shell script at: /home/rtf/Desktop/RTF/restoreSource.sh

flags.title: SQL Injection leading to Authentication Bypass

flagList.instructions: Exploit the SQL Injection in the form of the login page to gain unauthorized access to the application as the user 'user'.
flagList.hint: The executed SQL query is similar to: SELECT * from USERS where username=? AND password=?; The used DBMS is MySQL, use the character '#' to comment out the second part of the statement in a way the executed query looks like SELECT * from USERS where username='user';

flagList.instructions: Remediate the SQL Injection exposure in the MysqlUser loginUser(String username, String password) method in the persistence.dao.UserDAO.java class.
flagList.hint: Refactor the affected method using Java's PreparedStatement instead of Statement to safely parametrize the query.
